    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2618714773" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2618714773" />
    <a title="Tsung" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung"><img alt="Tsung" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298808605p2/4992851.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2618714773?book_show_action=true">Dec 07, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tsung" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tsung" href="/user/show/4992851-tsung">Tsung</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4992851-tsung?shelf=favourite">favourite</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2618714773" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14658434929943095395">This is a mesmerizing novel from Kawabata. The story revolves around two generations of two families, a villainess and an ingénue (the titular Thousand Cranes). Mr Mitani has not one, but two affairs, and both with the knowledge of his wife. His actions are not without consequence, creating ripples which rock both families, even after his death. Yet he is not the main character, as the story begins after his death. It is his son, Kikuji, who has to pick up the pieces, dealing with a tainted lega</span>
  <span id="freeText14658434929943095395" style="display:none">This is a mesmerizing novel from Kawabata. The story revolves around two generations of two families, a villainess and an ingénue (the titular Thousand Cranes). Mr Mitani has not one, but two affairs, and both with the knowledge of his wife. His actions are not without consequence, creating ripples which rock both families, even after his death. Yet he is not the main character, as the story begins after his death. It is his son, Kikuji, who has to pick up the pieces, dealing with a tainted legacy and two mistresses who are looking for closure. <br /><br /><i>Now, as he knelt with closed eyes before the ashes, her image failed to come to him; but the warmth of her touch enfolded him, making him drunk with its smell. A strange fact, but, because of the woman, a fact that seemed in no way unnatural. And although her touch was upon him, the sensation was less tactile than auditory, musical.</i><br /><br />The writing is beautiful, sensory and sensual. But it is the enigmatic characters, the intricate and complex relationships that make the story so intriguing. There is also an abundance of metaphors and symbolism. It needs to be read slowly to pick up on all the nuances. Somehow Kawabata manages to weave the interaction between characters around the Japanese tea ceremony and its associated ceramic ware. He makes Shino, Oribe and Raku ware sound so beautiful. If I had money to spare, I would not mind starting a collection of these precious antiques.<br /><br /><i>A faint red floated up from the white glaze. Kikuji reached to touch the voluptuous and warmly cool surface.</i><br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />Mr Mitani had a brief fling with Chikako, the wicked witch of the story, even with his wife knowing about it. He breaks off the affair, only to blatantly start another with the recently widowed Mrs Ota. Mrs Mitani sees Mrs Ota as more of a threat than the unmarriageable outcaste Chikako. She joins forces with Chikako to oppose Mrs Ota in any way they can. Mrs Mitani dies, which is construed as due to her husband’s affair with Mrs Ota.<br /><br />The older generation seems to pass on its desires, its guilt and it burdens to the next. Chikako and Mrs Ota both see Mr Mitani in Kikuji, and treat them almost as though they were one and the same person. Kikuji inherits these two women, along with feelings of guilt and dirtiness. He is at first disgusted at the appearance of the two women who had disgraced his own mother. Yet he was terribly conflicted, as though his father’s spirit was residing in him. His resolve gradually weakens and he gives in to Mrs Ota’s advances.<br /><br />Central to Chikako’s character is a physical flaw, a large birthmark over her breast. Much of her behaviour and her fate seem to stem from it. It is highly symbolic and represents ugliness, rejection and resentment. It was a source of embarrassment and an object of ridicule. But far from being a victim, Chikako was cunning, manipulative and deceitful. She went to great lengths to destroy any relationship between the Mitani and the Ota family lines. She orchestrated a <i>miai</i> for Kikuji and Inamura, the beautiful girl with the thousand cranes kerchief, to distract Kikuji from the Otas. Her actions were aptly described throughout as venomous.<br /><br />Among all the women in the story, Mrs Ota is the neediest and the weakest. She seems to need a man for security and fulfillment. Her daughter Fumiko is a mystery. More westernized than the rest, she is perhaps the most virtuous and clean character in the story. She is a filial and devoted daughter. Despite Mr Mitani’s immoral behaviour, she was even curiously subservient to him while he was still alive. Kikuji was definitely attracted to Inamura but he was obviously curious about Fumiko. But it is a bit of a shame that he rejects Inamura on account that their meeting was part of Chikako’s scheme.<br /><br /><i>Kikuji could not bring himself to say that the Shino bowl was like her mother. But the two bowls before then were like the souls of his father and her mother.</i><br /><br />The ceramic ware in the story could be characters in the story in their own right. It was fascinating how much meaning there could be in the choice of ceramic ware in the tea ceremony. Chikako presented a bowl in a veiled, spiteful attack on Mrs Ota. The bowl had passed through the hands of Mr Ota, Mrs Ota, Mr Mitani, Chikako and Kikuji. Kikuji tried to downplay the significance. <i>”It’s four hundred years old, after all – its history goes back to Momoyama and Rikyu himself. Tea masters have looked after it and passed it down through the centuries. My father is of very little importance.</i><br /><br />Fumiko also made use of a set of red and black Raku, “man-wife” teacups. Perhaps representing Mr Mitani and Mrs Ota. Kikuji initially took offence but eventually understood it as sentimentality on the part of Fumiko. <br /><br /><i>They both looked at the Shino. Before Mrs Ota’s ashes it had been a flower vase, and now it was back at its old work, a water jar in a tea ceremony… It had a strange career. But perhaps the strangeness was natural to tea vessels. In the three or four hundred years before it became the property of Mrs Ota, it had passed through the hands of people with what strange careers?</i><br /><br />In a final symbolic gesture, Kikuji gets Fumiko to shatter the Shino vase (probably valuable) which seemed to be breaking some kind of curse. This act releases both Kikuji and Fumiko from their parents and their past.<br /><br />In the end, we don’t know what happens with Kikuji and Fumiko. But the open ending suits the story.<br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I'll never see my tea cup the same way again...</span>
  <a data-text-id="14658434929943095395" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


